## Example: Populated `principles.md` (single-scope visual editor app)

This is a worked example of what a finished `.tenbo/principles.md` looks like for a single-scope project (visual editor for designing a design system, eight layers including Visual Canvas, AI Assistant, Tokens & Themes). It calibrates the expected voice, density, and section-by-section content. Adapt — don't copy verbatim.

```markdown
# Architecture Principles

This file captures the layering rules, naming conventions, and refactor heuristics that hold across the editor app. It is the canonical reference when deciding where new work belongs and when something has grown big enough to split.

## Layering rules

1. **Design Tokens & Themes is the source of truth for design values.** No other layer hard-codes a color, spacing value, or font size. They read tokens or the published stylesheet instead.
2. **The AI Assistant only changes the design system through the Tokens & Themes layer.** It never reaches around to write directly to the canvas or to other panels.
3. **The Visual Canvas owns what is on screen. The Property & Style Editor owns what the selected piece looks like.** Neither one writes into the other. They share state through the layer-tree selection only.
4. **Publish & Share is downstream of everything.** It reads the finished design system and emits files. It never edits tokens, components, or canvas state on the way out.

(...one rule per major layer responsibility, 6–10 total.)

## What counts as a violation

- A panel or canvas piece reads a color or spacing value from a literal string instead of a token.
- The AI Assistant writes to the database without going through validation first, or without an approval step on a destructive change.
- A new building block is created outside the Component Library.
- A roadmap item lives in the wrong layer because it was the easiest place to drop it, not because it actually belongs there.

(Each bullet is enforceable at review time. If you can't tell whether a PR violates it, the rule is too vague.)

## Naming conventions

- **Layer names use product language, not technical language.** "Visual Canvas", not "renderer".
- **Layer ids are kebab-case** and match the folder name under `.tenbo/scopes/<scope>/layers/`.
- **Roadmap item ids use the scope prefix** (e.g., `ed-` for editor scope) followed by a three-digit number; cross-scope items use `x-`.
- **Component types use PascalCase singular** (`Button`, `Input`); variant dimensions are short lowercase nouns (`size`, `color`).

## Refactor heuristics

- **Split a layer when it has more than ten roadmap items in flight or its plain-language narrative grows past 300 lines.**
- **Split a layer when its file count crosses the metric thresholds below.**
- **Promote a sub-concern into its own layer when it grows its own external dependencies, its own approval flow, or its own settings panel.**
- **Pull a deep-dive document out of a layer when its README starts answering "how" questions instead of "what" questions.**

## Metric thresholds

<!-- Machine-read by tenbo's metrics tool. Keep as flat key:value YAML. -->

```yaml
max_files_per_layer: 50
max_outbound_deps_per_layer: 5
max_lines_per_layer_total: 8000
max_days_intent_stale: 30
max_pct_roadmap_in_now: 20
```
```

**Calibration notes:**

- ~600–800 words is plenty. Longer = nobody reads it.
- The "What counts as a violation" section has no template hint — agents commonly skip or under-write it. The example is your nudge to make it concrete and enforceable.
- Keep thresholds at template defaults unless you have a specific reason to change them. Existing layers exceeding defaults are a refactor signal, not a reason to raise the threshold.
- Plain-English discipline applies — no "module", "API", "endpoint" in the prose. Inside the YAML threshold block, technical names (`max_files_per_layer`) are fine because that block is machine-read.
